open_comment: Some of the agree/disagree questions are worded as "pass as a man or woman" when it would probably be better (in my opinion) to say "pass as the gender you identify with." The current phrasing seems exclusionary to nonbinary people and I was sometimes unsure whether it meant passing as my assigned gender, my actual gender, or either.

A lot of the prompts were about passing as a man or woman. There needs to be more prompts for wanting to appear like neither/both/etc. I identify somewhere between non-binary and femme transman, and how I want to appear/seem to the others is most accurately described as "not a cis woman!" or a man in drag... or even a trans woman. I wouldn't mind passing as a man, but that's not my ideal appearance.

A lot of the questions about how others percieve me as trans depend entirely on who the "others" are. Like are they complete strangers, co-workers, friends, or other students? Because with friends, I am very open and everyone knows I'm trans. With complete strangers, I don't want them to know a single thing about me. As far as strangers go, I want to be a completely unknown void.

I find that many trans folks and non binary people have feelings of anxiety, guilt, shame, depression among other things. I think a list of negative feelings that you could check what you have would give a more accurate description of how we feel. Being mis gendered is a normsal reaction from people who have us programmed in their subconscious as the gender they new us for so long as. A better question would be something that made reference to how many times someone intentionally mis gendered us.

I'm physically disabled and have to wear braces on my legs. People stare at my legs/braces all the time. I answered all of the questions literally. So some questions I answered yes to e.g. being stared at but it was because of people staring at my legs not at other parts of my body necessarily.

On the being 'read' trans part, I would rather be seen as transgender man than a masc cis woman. Often for transmen, people don't know we 'are a thing' and assume we are masculine women or lesbians (which hurts a lot more), whereas a lot of my transfemme friends are immediately seen as a transgender person, and this comes with different issues for transfemme (immediately being attacked for being trans) and transmasc (being hushed and shunned as 'dykes') people.

They don't experience things like dysphoria or the same amount of discrimination and I, among others, find it offensive to imply that it is the same thing. I was born assigned-male in 1956. By the time I was 5 years old, I was aware of wishing that I could be a girl, and I began to hate my male name - this would plague me my entire life, right up to transition at age 59. All through my teens and 20's, I was in severe depression, which I now know was gender dysphoria. From age 29 to 57, I was happily married in a very convention cis-het marriage, and I was not in gender dysphoria or depression during those years. My wife died in 2013, and within 2 months, I was cross-dressing and in severe dysphoria again, and by the late summer of 2015, I was starting to lose my sense on identity: I didn't know who I was anymore. I joined a trans support group in January 2016, found a therapist in March 2016, and committed to transition on June 4th, 2016. Everything was cleared up by my transition. No more depression, and I have found joy in my life. I have a life-partner again, (another transwoman), my daughter (she is age 40), is 100% supportive and accepting of my transition, and I have actually a much better relationship with her now than I ever did while I was trying to be her "Dad". I consider my transgender identity to be truly a gift. I have been able to experience  life on both sides of the gender line, and both phases of my life have mostly been happy.

I'm not gender nonconforming and there was a whole group of questions that were specifically about people reacting to the gender nonconformity of the person taking the survey. As a cis passing, binary, gender conforming, transsexual man, that whole section didn't apply to me at all and was really weird to try to answer. I am seven years into my transition and I have been passing as a male for nearly that entire time. Not all trans people are gender nonconforming so you need to consider some kind of a "does not apply" option for those of us who are binary, cis passing, and gender conforming.
